pseudo's bundled openat2 wrapper is a stub that always returns ENOSYS
("for now, let's try just failing out hard, and hope things retry with
a different syscall"). That assumption breaks on this host: Ubuntu
26.04's tar (fixed for CVE-2025-45582) calls openat2() directly during
extraction and treats ENOSYS as fatal instead of retrying with plain
openat(), so every `do_package`/`do_rootfs` tar invocation under pseudo
fails with e.g. "tar: ./usr/include: Cannot mkdir: Function not
implemented".

This is backported from the real openat2 implementation posted
upstream (Mark Hatle, "[pseudo][PATCH 4/4] openat2: Implement openat2
wrapper", yocto-patches@lists.yoctoproject.org, Jan 2026), based on the
existing openat() wrapper (ports/linux/guts/openat.c). Two changes on
top of the upstream posting:

 - open_how's pointer is kept const throughout (including the
   wrapfuncs.in prototype below): glibc >= 2.39 declares openat2()'s
   third parameter const, which the original non-const wrapper
   prototype conflicts with under GCC ("conflicting types for
   'openat2'").

 - my_how.resolve is zeroed before the real syscall, and the syscall
   is passed &my_how (the masked copy) rather than the caller's
   original how. Upstream passes resolve constraints through
   unmodified ("The new resolve items should work, but are not
   processed by pseudo"); on this host, GNU tar's hardened extraction
   sets RESOLVE_* flags (its CVE-2025-45582 fix) that the real kernel
   then enforces for real, spuriously rejecting same-filesystem paths
   with EXDEV. pseudo is a build-time fakeroot with no real
   symlink/mount-crossing threat model to defend against, so it's safe
   to just drop those constraints.

